sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM clustering_sessions 
WHERE status = 'completed';

external_knowledge:
- "gardeners" refer to users who have performed clustering sessions;
- "types of seeds" refer to the clustering algorithms used;
- "plantings" refer to the number of times each algorithm was used.

sql:
SELECT method_name
FROM clustering_algorithms
WHERE scalability = 'Very large n_samples, medium n_clusters with MiniBatch code';

external_knowledge:
- "Pioneers in the data realm" refers to users who have created projects before running any clustering algorithms;
- "Sown the seeds of their projects" means users who have initiated projects;
- "Delving into the algorithms' garden" means users who have started using clustering algorithms;
- "Tools they wielded" refers to the clustering algorithms used in their most recent sessions;
- "Digital boundary of 100MB" refers to datasets larger than 100MB in size.

- A completed session is one where the status is 'completed';
- The K-Means algorithm is a popular clustering method used for partitioning data into a fixed number of clusters;
- The performance of the K-Means algorithm is evaluated using metrics such as execution time, accuracy, number of clusters created, and silhouette score.

- "Top-performing algorithms" are determined by ranking based on average execution time and average accuracy;
- "Most active users" are those who have received more than two notifications since January 1, 2022;
- The user with the highest average session time for each algorithm is considered the most active for that algorithm.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(setting_id)
FROM algorithm_settings
WHERE parameter_values LIKE '%damping=0.5%';

external_knowledge:
- 'Guardians of the projects' refers to users who have the role of 'owner' in the projects;
- 'Extent of their engagement' refers to the number of clustering sessions they have conducted;
- 'Weight of their data' refers to the average size of the datasets they use.

- 'Cultivated the most time-consuming yet precise clusters' refers to users with the highest average execution time and accuracy in their clustering sessions;
- 'Gardeners' are the users in the database;
- 'Tending to their clusters' refers to the execution of clustering algorithms.

- 'analyst' refers to a specific role within the organization;
- 'collaboration' refers to an instance where a user is involved in a project with other users;
- 'project' is a clustering project that users are assigned to.

- "shine like stars in the sky" refers to the top-performing algorithms;
- "brilliance" refers to the average accuracy of the clustering methods;
- "efficiency" refers to the average execution time, where a lower value indicates better performance.

sql:
SELECT method_name, geometry
FROM clustering_algorithms
ORDER BY method_name ASC;

external_knowledge:
- Active users are those whose `is_active` status is 1;
- Users with the role that can run clustering algorithms have permissions that include 'can_run_clustering';
- The clustering method with the minimum average execution time is considered the fastest performing method.

- 'guardians of the data kingdom' refers to users with the role 'admin';
- The average accuracy is calculated for projects where the role of the collaborator is 'admin';
- The query filters for an average accuracy greater than 0.5.

- "clustering journey" refers to the process where data points are grouped into clusters using specific algorithms;
- "sessions they are a part of" refers to the unique identifiers for each clustering session;
- "when these sessions began" refers to the start time of each clustering session.

- "Not scalable with n_samples" implies that the algorithms do not perform well as the number of samples increases;
- "born in the year 2022" refers to algorithms created between January 1, 2022, and December 31, 2022;
- "youngest to the oldest" means the results are ordered by the creation date in descending order, with the most recent algorithms first.

- "Clustering algorithms" are methods used in data science to group similar data points together;
- "Average execution time" refers to the mean time taken for the algorithm to complete its task over multiple runs;
- "Slowest to fastest" means the results are ordered from the highest average execution time to the lowest.
